reviewText: I had forgotten just how funny Jerry Lewis was.  In his early age and for the times, this was a hoot!  I enjoyed going back and remembering how simple things once were.  No sex, violence, cursing, just good clean fun by a natural born mess up!

At times slapstick, at other occasions verbally subtle, the humor of Sad Sack entertains. In this story, a womans face doesnt launch a thousand ships but triggers unfolding action. She is a nightclub entertainer as a singer and dancer who falls for Bixby, the protagonist. Bixby proposes to her, which proposal she accepts, Later, Bixbys buddy interferes resulting with the engagements end. Bixby reacts by doing something extreme yet fitting for the character. Dolan, Bixbys Army buddy, in his voice-over, says, Bixby doesnt react as would a typical guy, killing himself. Instead, Bixby does something drastic. He leaves a note announcing to everyone hes gone AWOL. He intends to join the French Foreign Legion but instead becomes involved with underworld types. In response, Dolan and another character successfully rescue Bixby. In the end, its not Bixby who gets the girl but Dolan.

The story drags a bit and the lack of Dean Martin is definitely felt. The plot feels almost like two movies crammed together. There's the movie about our hapless hero living and training on the army base and then there's the second story of the mission to Morocco. It's not without it's charms though and Lewis has some strong comedic moments, but it will be a while until he hits his stride as the star of the show.
